gh's School, Faringdon|St Hugh's School]], [[Faringdon]]\n*St John's Priory School, [[Banbury]]\n*St Mary's School, [[Henley-on-Thames]]\n*[[Summer Fields School]], [[Oxford]]\n*The Treehouse School, [[Cholsey]]\n*Valley School, [[Ascott-under-Wychwood]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Senior and all-through schools===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Abacus College, [[Headington]]\n*[[Abingdon School]], [[Abingdon-on-Thames]]\n*[[Bellerbys College]], [[Oxford]]\n*[[Bloxham School]], [[Bloxham]]\n*[[Carfax College]], [[Oxford]]\n*[[Cokethorpe School]], [[Witney]]\n*[[Cranford House School]], [[Wallingford, Oxfordshire|Wallingford]]\n*[[D'Overbroeck's College]], [[Oxford]]\n*EF Academy International Boarding School Oxford, [[Oxford]]\n*[[European School, Culham|European School]], [[Culham]]\n*[[Headington School]], [[Oxford]]\n*[[Kingham Hill School]], [[Chipping Norton]]\n*Kings Oxford, [[Oxford]]\n*[[King's School, Witney|King's School]], [[Witney]]\n*[[Magdalen College School, Oxford|Magdalen College School]], [[Oxford]]\n*[[Oxford Montessori Schools]], [[Elsfield]]\n*[[The Oratory School]], [[Woodcote]]\n*[[Our Lady's Abingdon]], [[Abingdon-on-Thames|Abingdon]]\n*[[Oxford High School, Oxford|Oxford High School]], [[Oxford]]\n*[[Oxford International College]], [[Oxford]]\n*Oxford Tutorial College, [[Oxford]]\n*[[Radley College]], [[Radley]]\n*[[Rye St Antony School]], [[Oxford]]\n*[[St Clare's, Oxford|St Clare's]], [[Oxford]]\n*[[St Edward's School, Oxford|St Edward's School]], [[Oxford]]\n*[[St Helen and St Katharine]], [[Abingdon-on-Thames]]\n*[[Shiplake College]], [[Shiplake]]\n*[[Sibford School]], [[Banbury]]\n*[[Tudor Hall School, Banbury|Tudor Hall School]], [[Banbury]]\n*[[Wychwood School]] [[Oxford]] \n{{div col end}}\n\n===Special and alternative schools===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Chilworth House School, [[Wheatley, Oxfordshire|Wheatley]]\n*Hillcrest Park School, [[Chipping Norton]]\n*Include Oxfordshire, [[Oxford]]\n*LVS Oxford, [[Begbroke]]\n*[[Mulberry Bush School]], [[Standlake]]\n*[[Parklands Campus]], [[Besselsleigh]]\n*[[Swalcliffe Park School]], [[Swalcliffe]]\n*The Unicorn School, [[Abingdon-on-Thames]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Further education===\n*[[Greene's Tutorial College]], [[Oxford]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.oxfordshire.gov.uk/cms/public-site/schools Schools], [[Oxfordshire County Council]]\n\n{{Schools in Oxfordshire}}\n{{Oxfordshire}}\n{{Schools in England}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Schools In Oxfordshire}}\n[[Category:Lists of schools in South East England|Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Schools in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Oxfordshire]]\n", "name_user": "Jpbowen", "label": "safe", "comment": "Many typo correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_schools_in_Oxfordshire"}
{"title_page": "John Mahoney", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = John Mahoney\n| image = John Mahoney 1994.JPG\n| caption = Mahoney in 1994\n| birth_name = Charles John Mahoney\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1940|6|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Blackpool]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2018|2|4|1940|6|20}}<!-- Reliable sources state Sunday, February 4, 2018. Please do not change to February 5. -->\n| death_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1977\u20132017\n}}\n'''Charles John Mahoney''' (June 20, 1940 \u2013 February 4, 2018<!-- Reliable sources state Sunday, February 4, 2018. Please do not change to February 5. -->) was an English-American actor. He first became known for his roles in such films as ''[[Moonstruck]]'' (1987), ''[[Eight Men Out]]'' (1988), ''[[Say Anything...]]'' (1989), ''[[Barton Fink]]'' (1991), and ''[[The Hudsucker Proxy]]'' (1994). He was best known for playing [[Martin Crane]] in the American sitcom ''[[Frasier]]'', which aired on [[NBC]] from 1993 to 2004. He also worked as a voice actor, and was passionate about his stage work on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] and in [[Chicago theatre]]. He won a [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play]] in 1986 for his performance in ''[[The House of Blue Leaves]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nCharles John Mahoney<ref>[https://scontent-sea1-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/fr/cp0/e15/q65/27752333_10213493714970982_2595739344544024592_n.jpg?efg=eyJpIjoidCJ9&oh=633fd8e473a326b3d72c1533e697266b&oe=5ADFC82C In U.S. Naturalization papers, he signed his name \"Charles John Mahoney\"] {{dead link|date=May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/feb/06/john-mahoney-obituary|title=John Mahoney obituary|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=February 6, 2018|accessdate=February 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206183642/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/feb/06/john-mahoney-obituary|archive-date=February 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> was born in the [[Bispham, Blackpool|Bispham]]{{cn|date=August 2019}} area of [[Blackpool]] on 20 June 1940, the seventh of eight children. His father, Reg, was a baker<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www-personal.umich.edu/~fwu/frasier/mahoney.html|title=John Mahoney (Martin Crane)|publisher=Personal.umich.edu|accessdate=October 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019082415/http://www-personal.umich.edu/~fwu/frasier/mahoney.html|archive-date=October 19, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> who played classical piano, and his mother, Margaret (n\u00e9e Watson), was a housewife who loved reading. His paternal grandfather was Irish.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/frasier-actor-john-mahoneys-early-14251811|title=Frasier actor John Mahoney's early life in Greater Manchester|publisher=Manchester Evening News|date=February 6, 2018|author=Dobson, Charlotte|access-date=February 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206150422/https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/frasier-actor-john-mahoneys-early-14251811|archive-date=February 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gorman|first1=Sophie|title=Sitcom star John Mahoney all set for festival return|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/theatre-arts/sitcom-star-john-mahoney-all-set-for-festival-return-30389547.html|accessdate=December 16, 2014|work=The Irish Independent|date=June 29, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216090424/http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/theatre-arts/sitcom-star-john-mahoney-all-set-for-festival-return-30389547.html|archive-date=December 16, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The family had been evacuated to Blackpool from their home city of [[Manchester]] when it was [[Manchester Blitz|heavily bombed]] during the [[Second World War]]. Mahoney started school at [[St Joseph's College, Blackpool|St Joseph's College]]. After the war, the family moved back to Manchester, where Mahoney grew up in the suburb of [[Withington]] and discovered acting at the [[Stretford Children's Theatre]]. His parents' marriage was not happy. They would not speak to each other for long periods of time; when they did, it often led to heated arguments. The family situation, combined with the war, fuelled Mahoney's interest in acting and he vowed to leave Manchester.<ref name=\"ChicagoTribune\">{{cite news|last=Kogan|first=Rick|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1996-05-17/features/9605170145_1_character-actor-crasher-steppenwolf-theatre|title=The Curse of John Mahoney|date=May 17, 1996|work=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=March 27, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502032507/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1996-05-17/features/9605170145_1_character-actor-crasher-steppenwolf-theatre|archive-date=May 2, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"TheGuardian\">{{cite news|last=Lane|first=Harriet|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2002/aug/04/features.review17|title=Take a chance on me|date=August 4, 2002|work=The Guardian|accessdate=March 27, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502001557/http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2002/aug/04/features.review17|archive-date=May 2, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMahoney moved to the United States aged 18 in March 1959,<ref>Illinois, Federal Naturalization Records, 1856-1991 for Charles John Mahoney, Petition Number: 479030</ref> when his older sister Vera (a [[war bride]] living in rural [[Illinois]]) agreed to sponsor him. He studied at [[Quincy University]] before joining the [[United States Army]]. After graduating from Quincy, he lived in [[Macomb, Illinois]], and earned his [[Master's degree]] in English<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/feb/06/john-mahoney-obituary|title=John Mahoney obituary|last=Hayward|first=Anthony|date=February 6, 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=October 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207041842/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/feb/06/john-mahoney-obituary|archive-date=February 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> from [[Western Illinois University]], where he went on to teach English in the early 1970s<ref name=Slate/> before settling in [[Forest Park, Illinois]], and later in [[Oak Park, Illinois]]. He became a U.S. citizen in 1971<ref>Northern District, Illinois, Naturalization Index, 1926-1979. Name:\tCharles John Mahoney\nAge:\t31\nBirth Year:\t1940\nNaturalization Year:\t1971\nNaturalization Place:\tChicago, Cook, Illinois, USA</ref> and served as editor of a [[medical journal]] through much of the 1970s.<ref name=Slate>Matthew Dessem (2018) [https://slate.com/culture/2018/02/frasier-actor-john-mahoney-has-died-at-77.html \"Actor John Mahoney Has Died at 77\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206190727/https://slate.com/culture/2018/02/frasier-actor-john-mahoney-has-died-at-77.html |date=February 6, 2018 }}, ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', February 6, 2018; accessed February 7, 2018.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Early work===\nDissatisfied with his career, Mahoney took acting classes at St. Nicholas Theatre, which inspired him to resign from his day job and pursue acting full-time. After a stage production in Chicago in 1977, [[John Malkovich]] encouraged him to join the [[Steppenwolf Theatre]].<ref name=ChicagoTribuneObit>Chris Jones (2018) [http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/theater/news/ct-ent-john-mahoney-dead-steppenwolf-frasier-20180205-story.html \"John Mahoney, Steppenwolf and 'Frasier' actor who walked away from Hollywood, dead at 77\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206045841/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/theater/news/ct-ent-john-mahoney-dead-steppenwolf-frasier-20180205-story.html |date=February 6, 2018 }} ''Chicago Tribune'', February 5, 2018. Accessed February 5, 2018.</ref><ref name=VanityFair>Julie Miller (2018) [https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/02/john-mahoney-dead \"John Mahoney, Beloved Frasier Father, Dies at 77\"], ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', February 5, 2018. Accessed February 6, 2018.</ref> He did so and went on to win the [[Clarence Derwent Award]] as Most Promising Male Newcomer. [[Gary Sinise]] said in an interview for ''[[Bomb Magazine]]'' that Lyle Kessler's play ''[[Orphans (Lyle Kessler play)|Orphans]]'' \"kicked John Mahoney, Kevin Anderson and Terry Kinney off into the movie business\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Loud |first=Lance |url=http://bombsite.com/issues/66/articles/2193 |title=BOMB Magazine: Gary Sinise by Scott Elliott |work=Bomb |accessdate=February 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320102326/http://bombsite.com/issues/66/articles/2193 |archivedate=March 20, 2012  }}</ref> after their Steppenwolf performance of the play for which he won the Derwent Award and the Theatre World Award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.steppenwolf.org/ensemble/members/details.aspx?id=43 |title=In 1986 |publisher=Steppenwolf.org |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111045452/http://www.steppenwolf.org/ensemble/members/details.aspx?id=43 |archive-date=November 11, 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Mahoney won [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]]'s [[Tony Award]] for Best Featured Actor in a Play for his performance in [[John Guare]]'s ''[[The House of Blue Leaves]]''.<ref name=NYT>Associated Press (2018) [https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/02/05/us/ap-us-obit-john-mahoney.html \"John Mahoney, Who Played Cranky Dad on 'Frasier,' Dies at 77\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206190321/https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/02/05/us/ap-us-obit-john-mahoney.html |date=February 6, 2018 }} ''[[The New York Times]]'', February 6, 2018. Accessed February 6, 2018.</ref>\n\nMahoney's first major film roles were in the 1987 [[Barry Levinson]] film ''[[Tin Men]]'' and ''[[Suspect (1987 film)|Suspect]]'', directed by [[Peter Yates]], which was a courtroom drama/mystery starring Cher, Dennis Quaid, and a young Liam Neeson. He went on to have prominent roles in a number of acclaimed films throughout the late 1980s and 1990s, including ''[[Moonstruck (film)|Moonstruck]]'', ''[[Eight Men Out]]'', ''[[Say Anything...]]'', ''[[In the Line of Fire]]'', ''[[Reality Bites]]'', and ''[[The American President]]''.<ref name=NYT/><ref name=TheGuardian2/><ref name=Slate/> He appeared in two [[Coen brothers]] films, ''[[Barton Fink]]''<ref name=BartonFink>Christoper Orr (2014) [https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/09/30-years-of-coens-barton-fink/379990/ \"30 Years of Coens: ''Barton Fink''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306225547/https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/09/30-years-of-coens-barton-fink/379990/ |date=March 6, 2018 }}, ''[[The Atlantic]]'', September 11, 2014. Accessed February 6, 2018.</ref> and ''[[The Hudsucker Proxy]]''.<ref name=Hudsucker>Christoper Orr (2014) [https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/09/30-years-of-coens-the-hudsucker-proxy/380068/ \"30 Years of Coens: ''The Hudsucker Proxy''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707201321/https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/09/30-years-of-coens-the-hudsucker-proxy/380068/ |date=July 7, 2017 }}, ''[[The Atlantic]]'', September 12, 2014. Accessed February 6, 2018.</ref>\n\nMahoney also played a pivotal gay role in Greg Berlanti's 2000 [[GLAAD Media Award|GLAAD]]-Award winning film ''[[The Broken Hearts Club: A Romantic Comedy]]''.\n\n===''Frasier''===\n{{main|Martin Crane}}\n\nMahoney appeared in ''[[Frasier]]'' from its debut in 1993 until the final episode in 2004; Mahoney received two [[Emmy Awards|Emmy]] nominations and two [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe]] nominations for the role of [[Martin Crane]], the father of [[Frasier Crane]] and [[Niles Crane]]. NBC executives held Mahoney in such high esteem that [[Warren Littlefield]] declared he was pre-approved when the ''Frasier'' creative team suggested casting him as the father.<ref>{{cite web |last=Levine |first=Ken |url=http://kenlevine.blogspot.com/2010/12/how-frasier-came-to-be.html |title=How Frasier Came to Be |publisher=Kenlevine.blogspot.com |date=December 15, 2010 |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120911170535/http://kenlevine.blogspot.com/2010/12/how-frasier-came-to-be.html |archive-date=September 11, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Prior to appearing on the series, Mahoney had appeared in an episode of ''[[Cheers]]'' \u2013 from which ''Frasier'' was a spinoff \u2013 as an inept jingle writer who has a brief conversation with Frasier. Mahoney also appeared as a priest in ''[[Becker (TV series)|Becker]]'', which starred ''Cheers'' star [[Ted Danson]].\n\n===Voice acting===\n[[File:John Mahoney.jpg|thumb|right|Mahoney voice acting in 2007]]\nMahoney's first voice job was in [[W. B. Yeats]]'s \"The Words upon the Window-Pane\" for the award-winning [[National Radio Theater]] of [[Chicago]]. He provided the [[Voice acting|voices]] for several characters in ''[[Antz]]'' (1998), Preston Whitmore in ''[[Atlantis: The Lost Empire]]'' and ''[[Atlantis: Milo's Return]]'', General Rogard in ''[[The Iron Giant]]'' (1999), and Papi in ''[[Kronk's New Groove]]'' (but was succeeded by [[Jeff Bennett]] in ''[[The Emperor's New School]]'' for an unknown reason). In 2007, Mahoney provided the voice of Dr. Robert Terwilliger, Sr. ([[Sideshow Bob]]'s father) in ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Funeral for a Fiend]].\" This reunited him with his ''[[Frasier]]'' co-stars [[Kelsey Grammer]] (Sideshow Bob) and [[David Hyde Pierce]] (Cecil, Sideshow Bob's brother).\n\n===Post-''Frasier''===\nMahoney co-starred as the Old Man in the Broadway revival of ''[[Prelude to a Kiss (play)|Prelude to a Kiss]]'' at the American Airlines Theater in a limited-run engagement running from previews on February 17, 2007, through to April 29, 2007.<ref>{{cite web |author=The Broadway League |url=http://www.ibdb.com/production.asp?ID=455728 |title=Internet Broadway Database: ''Prelude to a Kiss'' |publisher=Ibdb.com |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071015232129/http://ibdb.com/production.asp?ID=455728 |archive-date=October 15, 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadway.com/gen/Buzz_Story.aspx?ci=542370 |title=Mahoney, Parisse, Tudyk to Headline Roundabout's ''Prelude to a Kiss'' |publisher=Broadway.com |date=August 1, 2012 |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071024124732/http://www.broadway.com/gen/Buzz_Story.aspx?ci=542370 |archive-date=October 24, 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> He appeared as an elderly [[drag queen]] in the ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' season 13 episode \"Somebody to Love,\" and co-starred with [[Steve Carell]] (himself a veteran of [[Chicago theatre]]) as the father of Carell's character in ''[[Dan in Real Life]]''. In March 2008, he opened in the world premiere of ''Better Late'' at the [[Theatre in Chicago|Northlight Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theatreinchicago.com/newswire.php?newsID=443 | title=Northlight Theatre set for The Outgoing Tide | publisher=Theatre in Chicago | date=April 20, 2011 | accessdate=October 14, 2012 | agency=Associated Press | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016061821/http://www.theatreinchicago.com/newswire.php?newsID=443 | archive-date=October 16, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> He was also the narrator for Midwest Airlines commercials. Mahoney also made two appearances on [[USA Network|USA]]'s ''[[Burn Notice]]'' in the [[Burn Notice (season 2)|second]] (2009) and [[Burn Notice (season 3)|third]] (2010) season finales. His character, referred to only as \"Management,\" is a senior intelligence agency official who is the apparent main mover of the conspiracy which [[blacklist]]ed [[Michael Westen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usanetwork.com/series/burnnotice/ |title=Burn Notice |publisher=usanetwork.com |date=October 8, 2012 |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007123557/http://www2.usanetwork.com/series/burnnotice/ |archive-date=October 7, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/burn-notice-company-man-back-in-from-the-cold | title=Review: 'Burn Notice' \u2013 'Company Man': Back in from the cold? | publisher=hitfix | date=June 23, 2011 | accessdate=October 14, 2012 | author=Sepinwall, Alan | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909071801/http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/burn-notice-company-man-back-in-from-the-cold | archive-date=September 9, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMahoney joined the cast of ''[[In Treatment (U.S. TV series)|In Treatment]]'' for the series' second season (2009) as a frenetic CEO who is overwhelmed by his personal and professional responsibilities and experiences chronic physical anxiety attacks. In 2010, he made a guest appearance on ''[[$h*! My Dad Says|$#@! My Dad Says]]'' as [[Homophobia|homophobic]] retired naval officer Lt. Commander Wally Durham. Despite the numerous successes throughout his career, Mahoney has maintained that his early work in [[Lyle Kessler]]'s play ''[[Orphans (Lyle Kessler play)|Orphans]]'' has \"affected people more than any other play I've ever done. I still get mail from it, I still get people stopping me on the street, and it's 20 years later.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.steppenwolf.org/watchlisten/backstage/detail.aspx?id=35 |title=Associate Artistic Director Curt Columbus Speaks With Kevin Anderson and John Mahoney &#124; Watch & Listen &#124; Steppenwolf Theatre Company |publisher=Steppenwolf.org |accessdate=February 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107232900/http://www.steppenwolf.org/watchlisten/backstage/detail.aspx?id=35 |archive-date=November 7, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nBeginning in April 2011, Mahoney began rehearsing ''The Outgoing Tide'', a new play by Bruce Graham at Northlight Theatre in [[Skokie, Illinois]] ([[suburban Chicago]]). The play also stars fellow ''Chicago'' actors [[Rondi Reed]] and Thom Cox. In 2011, he had two guest appearances on ''[[Hot in Cleveland]]'' as Roy, a waiter and a love interest for [[Betty White]]'s character Elka.<ref name=dispatch>{{cite news|last1=Rousseau|first1=Caryn|title=After 'Frasier,' John Mahoney happy to be back in roles onstage|url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/life_and_entertainment/2014/03/14/after-frasier-actor-happy-to-be-back-in-roles-onstage.html|accessdate=November 21, 2014|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|publisher=John F. Wolfe|date=March 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129112239/http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/life_and_entertainment/2014/03/14/after-frasier-actor-happy-to-be-back-in-roles-onstage.html|archive-date=November 29, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> This reunited him with his ''[[Frasier]]'' co-star [[Jane Leeves]], as well as [[Wendie Malick]] whose character he eventually married in ''Frasier'' and his co-star in the movie ''[[The American President]]''. Mahoney was a featured ensemble cast member in ''The Birthday Party'', playing in Chicago's [[Steppenwolf Theatre]] from January 24 to April 28, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.steppenwolf.org/Plays-Events/productions/index.aspx?id=564|title=The Birthday Party|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424231529/http://www.steppenwolf.org/Plays-Events/productions/index.aspx?id=564|archivedate=April 24, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Mahoney portrayed his last role in the play ''The Rembrandt'', from September to November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.steppenwolf.org/tickets--events/seasons/2017-18/the-rembrandt/|title=The Rembrandt|website=Steppenwolf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180131141632/https://www.steppenwolf.org/tickets--events/seasons/2017-18/the-rembrandt/|archive-date=January 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.steppenwolf.org/tickets--events/seasons/2017-18/the-rembrandt/ |title=The Rembrandt |access-date=February 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180131141632/https://www.steppenwolf.org/tickets--events/seasons/2017-18/the-rembrandt/ |archive-date=January 31, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAlong with [[David Hyde Pierce]], Mahoney was godfather to ''Frasier'' co-star [[Jane Leeves]]' son Finn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bebe-neuwirth.musicnewshq.com/news/frasier-finale-10th-anniversary-the-cast-then-and-now-reporter-times-parade-entertainment/show|title=Frasier Finale 10th Anniversary: The Cast Then and Now|publisher=musicnewshq.com|access-date=December 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221165039/http://bebe-neuwirth.musicnewshq.com/news/frasier-finale-10th-anniversary-the-cast-then-and-now-reporter-times-parade-entertainment/show|archive-date=December 21, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Mahoney rarely spoke publicly about his private life,<ref name=\"ChicagoTribune\"/> but in a 2002 article he revealed he had been in several relationships, although he had never married, citing his parents' unhappy marriage as something he feared he would repeat.<ref name=\"TheGuardian\"/> He suffered from [[colon cancer]] in the mid-1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/chicago/theater/john-mahoney-interview|title=John Mahoney - Interview|accessdate=February 6, 2018|date=April 1, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206041302/https://www.timeout.com/chicago/theater/john-mahoney-interview|archive-date=February 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> His Catholic faith was at the center of his life and work.<ref>The God Factor: Inside the Spiritual Lives of Public People  Cathleen Falsani, Author . Sarah Crichton Books/Farrar, Straus & Giroux (272p) {{ISBN|978-0-374-16381-5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://aleteia.org/blogs/deacon-greg-kandra/rip-john-mahoney-ive-always-prayed-to-the-holy-ghost-for-wisdom-understanding-and-knowledge/ |title=RIP, John Mahoney: 'I've always prayed to the Holy Ghost for wisdom, understanding and knowledge' |access-date=February 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180211071901/https://aleteia.org/blogs/deacon-greg-kandra/rip-john-mahoney-ive-always-prayed-to-the-holy-ghost-for-wisdom-understanding-and-knowledge/ |archive-date=February 11, 2018 |url-status=live |date=February 6, 2018 }}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=August 2019}}\n\nMahoney lived in [[Oak Park, Illinois]].<ref name=\"TheGuardian\"/>\n\n==Death==\nMahoney died in a [[Chicago]] hospice on February 4, 2018, of [[Complication (medicine)|complications]] from [[throat cancer]], originally diagnosed in 2014. He was 77 years old. According to his friend [[Anna Shapiro]], \"He was fragile and he was supposed to be having a routine procedure. But having just beat Stage 3 throat cancer, I think he was just too weak... by the time he did ''The Rembrandt'' [a play at [[Steppenwolf Theatre Company|Steppenwolf Theatre]]] he was clean of cancer... but other health issues came up and he was just too fragile.\"<ref>\n* {{Cite news|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/steppenwolf-ensemble-member-actor-john-mahoney-has-died-starred-in-frazier/|title=Steppenwolf ensemble member John Mahoney has died, starred in 'Frasier'|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|access-date=February 7, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207010343/https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/steppenwolf-ensemble-member-actor-john-mahoney-has-died-starred-in-frazier/|archive-date=February 7, 2018|url-status=live}}<!-- Reliable sources state Sunday, February 4, 2018. Please do not change to February 5. -->\n* {{cite news|last1=Chuba|first1=Kirsten|title='Frasier' Star John Mahoney Dies at 77|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/john-mahoney-dead-dies-frasier-1202688144/|newspaper=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=February 5, 2018|access-date=February 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210135254/http://variety.com/2018/tv/news/john-mahoney-dead-dies-frasier-1202688144/|archive-date=February 10, 2018|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite news|last1=Morton|first1=Victor|title='Frasier' dad John Mahoney reportedly dies at 77|url=http://washingtontimes.com/news/2018/feb/5/john-mahoney-frasier-dad-dies-77/|newspaper=[[The Washington Times]]|date=February 5, 2018|access-date=February 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206071950/https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2018/feb/5/john-mahoney-frasier-dad-dies-77/|archive-date=February 6, 2018|url-status=live}}\n* {{Cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-mahoney-dead-frasier-actor-was-77-1081939|title=John Mahoney, the Cantankerous Dad on 'Frasier,' Dies at 77|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=February 7, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206042432/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-mahoney-dead-frasier-actor-was-77-1081939|archive-date=February 6, 2018|url-status=live}}\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/theater/news/ct-ent-john-mahoney-dead-steppenwolf-frasier-20180205-story.html|title=John Mahoney, Steppenwolf and 'Frasier' actor who walked away from Hollywood, dead at 77|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=February 6, 2018|accessdate=February 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205233307/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/theater/news/ct-ent-john-mahoney-dead-steppenwolf-frasier-20180205-story.html|archive-date=February 5, 2018|url-status=live}}\n* {{Cite news|url=https://video.wttw.com/video/john-mahoney-francis-guinan-discuss-rembrandt-lvwne0/|title=John Mahoney, Francis Guinan Discuss 'The Rembrandt'|date=August 31, 2017|work=[[WTTW]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603195922/https://video.wttw.com/video/john-mahoney-francis-guinan-discuss-rembrandt-lvwne0/|archive-date=June 3, 2019|url-status=live|access-date= June 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''Hudson Taylor''\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''Mission Hill''\n| Michael Doyle\n|\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[The Killing Floor (1984 film)|The Killing Floor]]''\n|factory representative\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Code of Silence (1985 film)|Code of Silence]]''\n| Prowler Representative\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[The Manhattan Project (film)|The Manhattan Project]]''\n| Lt. Col. Conroy\n| \n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[The Christmas Gift]]''\n| The Town Mayor\n| \n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Streets of Gold (film)|Streets of Gold]]''\n| Linnehan\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Tin Men]]''\n| Moe Adams\n| <ref name=NYT/>\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Suspect (1987 film)|Suspect]]''\n| Judge Matthew Bishop Helms\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Moonstruck]]''\n| Perry\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Frantic (film)|Frantic]]''\n| Williams, U.S. Embassy Official\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Betrayed (1988 film)|Betrayed]]''\n| Shorty\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Eight Men Out]]''\n| [[Kid Gleason|William \"Kid\" Gleason]]\n| <ref name=NYT/>\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Say Anything...]]''\n| James Court\n| <ref name=TheGuardian2/>\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Love Hurts (1991 film)|Love Hurts]]''\n| Boomer\n|\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[The Russia House (film)|The Russia House]]''\n| Brady\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Barton Fink]]''\n| W. P. Mayhew\n| <ref name=BartonFink/>\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Article 99]]''\n| Dr. Henry Dreyfoos\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[In the Line of Fire]]''\n| Sam Campagna\n| <ref name=TheGuardian2>[https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/feb/06/john-mahoney-who-played-frasiers-martin-crane-dies-aged-77 \"John Mahoney, who played Frasier's Martin Crane, dies aged 77\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/